# AUTHORED-BY Claude Fable 5
#
# Machine-readable normative-statement companion for "Access-Controlled SPARQL Query
# over a Solid Pod" (https://jeswr.github.io/solid-sparql-query/ — the AC-SPARQL
# Editor's Draft). COMPLEMENTARY: the full-text spec is the normative document and is
# unchanged; this graph enumerates its normative statements so tooling (conformance
# suites, the interop map, coverage gates, the solid-server-rs implementation work)
# can consume them.
#
# Model: the Solid Protocol's own requirement markup (http://www.w3.org/ns/spec#) as a
# sidecar graph, + the certification testability spine (E / A-int / A-exist / P), +
# honest per-statement test-gap accounting — the jeswr/spec-companion format
# (shapes/spec-companion.shape.ttl + tools/validate.mjs in that repo). Statement texts
# are VERBATIM quotes of the pinned spec source (validator-enforced against index.html —
# tags stripped, entities decoded, [[refs]] unbracketed so a quote spanning a citation
# reads e.g. "SPARQL11-PROTOCOL", whitespace collapsed; an empty ReSpec cross-reference
# <a href="#x"></a> vanishes, leaving "()" or a dangling "per" in several quotes, each
# noted on the statement).
#
# Testability adjudication policy used here (documented so it is reviewable):
#   E       — deterministically black-box testable (a concrete request/response pair
#             decides it; the spec's informative Conformance Test Scenarios section
#             seeds these).
#   A-int   — a universal non-interference / uniformity property ("MUST NOT vary in
#             any way", "MUST be a function of X only"): samplable by paired-scenario
#             vectors, not exhaustively decidable black-box.
#   A-exist — audit/inspection only (internal evaluation order, "same rigour",
#             architectural freedoms).
#   P       — not testable as specified (carries a justifying sc:testGap).
#
# Validate (from a sibling jeswr/spec-companion checkout):
#   node ../spec-companion/tools/validate.mjs spec.statements.ttl --spec-html index.html

@base <https://jeswr.github.io/solid-sparql-query/spec.statements.ttl> .
@prefix sc:      <https://w3id.org/jeswr/spec-companion#> .
@prefix spec:    <http://www.w3.org/ns/spec#> .
@prefix dcterms: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> .
@prefix prov:    <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#> .
@prefix rdfs:    <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd:     <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

#################################################################
# The companion document
#################################################################

<> a sc:CompanionDocument ;
    dcterms:title "Access-Controlled SPARQL Query normative-statement companion"@en ;
    sc:companionOf <https://jeswr.github.io/solid-sparql-query/> ;
    sc:specVersion "498b288025c1862cbe384bcaa400a415a95a0a3c" ;
    dcterms:created "2026-07-06"^^xsd:date ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo <https://jeswr.org/#me> ;
    dcterms:description "Extracted with AI assistance (Claude Fable 5, Anthropic) from the pinned spec source; awaiting review by the human editor, like the spec itself."@en ;
    sc:extractionNote "The GET-equivalence governing sentence (#read-visibility: 'a named graph is part of a requester's authorized dataset if and only if the corresponding resource is readable by that requester') carries no BCP 14 keyword; it is enforced through ACSQ-AD-1/ACSQ-AD-2. Errata candidate: give #read-visibility a MUST." ;
    sc:extractionNote "'Only readability governs visibility. No other access mode (write, append, control) grants or denies query visibility.' (#read-visibility) is a keywordless normative clause; enforced via the authorized-dataset construction (ACSQ-AD-1). Errata candidate." ;
    sc:extractionNote "Non-disclosure invariant 1 (Bindings, #non-disclosure-invariants) uses lowercase 'may' with mandatory intent ('no ASK answer may be derived from a graph outside the authorized dataset'); RFC 8174 reserves only uppercase forms. Enforced via ACSQ-ND-1 and ACSQ-AD-2. Errata candidate: rephrase with MUST NOT." ;
    sc:extractionNote "Non-disclosure invariant 3's tail ('a count may never differ because of unreadable content') uses lowercase 'may'; the MUST in the same sentence (ACSQ-ND-4) carries the requirement. Errata candidate." ;
    sc:extractionNote "The #location note says clients 'must not assume this convention' (the <storage root>sparql layout) in lowercase inside an informative note; errata candidate: promote to a normative client requirement in #discovery." ;
    sc:extractionNote "The #namespaces note says 'implementations should treat the IRIs as defined by this specification' in lowercase inside an informative note; errata candidate if normative force is intended." ;
    sc:extractionNote "The #authorized-dataset post-filtering bullet ('Evaluating the query over any larger dataset and filtering solutions afterwards (post-filtering) does not satisfy this requirement, even if the final solution sequence coincides') is a keywordless normative elaboration of ACSQ-AD-2; recorded here rather than as a statement." ;
    sc:extractionNote "The #udg-request semantics paragraphs ('When the reserved IRI appears among a query's default-graph IRIs, the default graph of that query's dataset is the merge of ...' and the named-graphs-remain-standing refinement) are keywordless definitional prose; conformance to them hangs on ACSQ-UDG-3's MUST honour. Errata candidate: add keywords or an explicit conformance hook." .

